Eulogia Praxis stands in the middle of an ornate tile floor.
It’s a ballroom. She’s only been here once or twice before, but she waltzes in like nothing could be more natural.

She’s not wearing the standard outfit people who have met her before or seen a depiction of her for whatever reason would recognize; the pajama-like dress and out-of-place headphones obscuring a black hair bow. Instead, she’s wearing something in between a suit and a dress, something pure white, like a mannequin. She holds within her hands a baton.
She bows, hand in front of her chest.
“Hello, everyone.”

She returns to standing up straight.
“My name is Eulogia Praxis.”
She’s standing proud and tall. She’s clearly the same girl, but none of the vaguely sickly feeling behavior of the old Eulogia remains.
“I understand some of you might be confused and scared. I’m sorry about that. Both the parts I do and don’t know about.” She frowns.
Eulogia quickly returns to a pleasant smile, however. She’s doing her best, recalling all the dictation her mother provided on manners before giving up on integrating her into society.

“In summary, the rest of the royal family have become unfit to serve. Death, unknown whereabouts, physical absence, and problems of temperament have made all of them either unable to take the role of a monarch, or harmful when doing so. I will accept this burden on their behalf.”

“I believe my father’s greatest mistake was his inaction. More than any outright cruelty, he simply ignored much of the suffering of the people he should have been caring for.” Eulogia is still smiling, but her eyes look to the side, obviously less pleased to talk about this part.
“This isn’t a result of any ill intent. I truly believe that. Think I’m biased if you will. But I cannot deny it was a mistake. I will be a much more… active ruler!”

She puts a finger to her chin. “I haven’t decided on a title, actually… I can’t be the king, so would that make me queen? That feels odd. I suppose there’s some time to decide. I don’t mind if anyone just calls me Eulogia, anyway! Just happy to talk.” She closes her eyes with a wide grin saying this, then opens them again. There’s a far-away stare to them.

“I know it’s scary. When things change. I think everyone feels like that in their own way. But I am more than my father or mother. Far from ignoring systemic issues I could be making policies related to, I am much more tangibly capable of improving people’s lives in many ways, and it would be improper of me to not attempt to.”

She slams the baton down into her open palm a few times, as an idle action. “I am a powerful user of magic! I will bring Arctica into a new world of peace and love. No one will have to be alone or in pain. I just need to figure a few things out first. Excuse the rocky transitionary period.”
“Please look forward to it!” She waves.

No one would ever be able to quite explain how it happened, or easily verbalize the experience. But upon the moment in time at this location when ‘Chapter 16’ of The Antarctica Project began, everyone within a certain radius of the royal palace, large enough to include the entire capital, would witness this scene.

She’s distressed herself, honestly. Housing someone else feels *wrong*. It brings to mind conflicted memories of her son, and her daughter, and her daughter and her granddaughter. Not conflicted referring to the emotions they provoke. Conflicted in terms of mutual exclusivity.
So she steps out of the house after a particularly uncomfortable moment. Maybe she’ll go check up on what’s going on. She *does* need to keep up on current events to sustain herself financially.
Bonnie wonders why someone would be given a name that sounds like ‘eulogy’. It just seems like asking for the kid to turn out depressed.
She doesn’t really get it.
Eulogia Praxis is breaking down. None of this should be happening. Nothing is right.
(She doesn’t consider the fact that she technically shouldn’t even really be alive. But I digress. It is certainly a technicality.)

The distorted nature of time within spaces such as these create various contrivances and inconveniences, and concentrated immediately in a small bubble around her, she experiences a brief eternity. Not quite that long. But she mulls in her trauma at length while free-falling to the floor in front of two people woefully unequipped to restrain a shut-in deluded into being a god. She relives moments she’s repressed, moments she’s forgotten, and moment she’s been forced by others to repress or forget.
She projects that outward. A diorama of the past half-overtakes the world. Her slipping control provides room for other influences. Things are about to get unusual.
Detlef Praxis, in a secure central location within the premises, finishes whatever pep-talk/strategy session he was in, and sends his men, the ones he could round up, out to do their job.

…His men. It’s a curious turn of phrase. They’re Frank’s men. But someone has to do this now, he guesses. He tends to be shoved into roles that need filling a lot. Like, almost exclusively. He kind of lacks any actual identity, he thinks.
He hopes those The Antarctica Project guys from Earth don’t get caught up in any of this. Probably not. Dextrum would’ve made sure, he bets.

Catarina Praxis, or “Neko” as she prefers to be called within this context, is smiling maniacally. She’s having the time of her life. This moment is exactly as she’d hoped. She had a participant in the palm of her hand, even if Wress had pussied out over what participant it was. She had incredible destructive power. And she had the element of surprise.
She gives a thumbs up to her boy Skelt, currently recording as much of this part as he can for propaganda purposes.

She wonders how her mother will cope with this. Probably in some completely over-the-top and insane way. It’s probably gonna leave her completely heartbroken and unable to go on even if she survives this.
Well, whatever.
She doesn’t care about that. Virtos Dextrum is more important at the moment.
But what about you, @We? You're where you always are, I guess. Your most direct influence, though...

Voreverl glares at Violetta "Great secret, never knew objects could be thrown! My war plans have been completely overturned by this revolutionary technique! Truly, I am thrilled to see what trick you think of next."
She mutters obscenities. “I’ve freed us both. From here on out… no one can interfere.” She looks at the sky. “Not even you.”

"I don't give a shit about this... what even is this? Some kind of skin deep philosophical garbage? Technology was the real villain all along! Except no, it wasn't, it was just a tool for me! I can still throw you off this roof, how's that for interfering, huh!? Wanna test your luck that you're as sturdy as that PDA?"
“I’d love to. I’d love you to have anything to provide that isn’t meaningless bullshit. But I’m not holding out hope.” She takes a deep breath.

"I don't 'provide'. I take away from others. I burn down societies, tear it apart at the seams, and leave nothing left! You sure aren't giving me anything valuable here. Is that gonna change, or do you really want to see the power of Voreverl Leocot firsthand?"
"I could start with the 'amazing endgame twist' you were probably going to get eventually. Hope you're not too weak to handle it." She looks to the side, annoyed.

"Sure, go ahead, dazzle me with your all-seeing eye of time-wasting. I've got nothing better to do while my minion finishes their job. Might as well demonstrate my indomitable will to the masses who don't know their place."
She stares ahead at nothing in particular. "None of it's real, Jane. It's all a farce."

Voreverl's hands tighten into fists "The only farce here is your understanding of who you're talking to! ...Ugh, whatever! I know Arctica is a simulation or something, okay!? That was like months ago! ...In your time, at least."
"No. This." She gestures around. "They made us. Something like that. Big whoop." Violetta shrugs. "It's not like it actually matters to anyone."

Voreverl stares at Violetta, taking in the words. Something almost comes out of her mouth several times, but instead she just looks around her, taking in the view. Eventually, it's too much to bear, and the floodgates open. "Gw...

GWEHEHEHEHEHEHEHEHEHEH! GWEHAHAHAH! GWEHHHHAAHAHAAAAA!" She lowers herself onto the rooftop and begins holding her stomach, kicking her legs, and quite literally rolling around laughing. "I am *such* a dumbass!"
"Yeah."

She calms down a bit, and just lays still, arms out, staring at the sky, grinning ear to ear. "Ever since... Avdol told me where I came from. I was actually *worried* about not being real! Gwehah! Imagine that! Voreverl Leocot turning out to the least real person in the world! It's ridiculous! But now... the playing field's been evened out! ...I would have closed the gap anyway, of course."

"Voreverl Leocot isn't real, obviously. But congratulations on whatever epiphany you think you had. I tried to convince myself it meant something for a bit, but even if it's true, it means nothing. My life and my actions are still things I have to live with, and so are yours." She stares down at you. "I don't really care about the project. Not directly. I cared about John Leiblich."

"That makes one of us. What, you Jane's secret twin? That another one of your big bombshells that mean nothing? Can't imagine what business you'd have with that douche, aside from like-minds attracting one another."

"I thought he might know something. ...About her. About me. And about what's been happening more generally, I guess. But the man was impenetrable, and then he died. I figured it out, though. I should have noticed the key earlier. Obviously the thing that spawned you would also lie about his name." She smirks, and kicks you in the side.

"Ow! Fuck off!" She stumbles to her feet "Voreverl Leocot *is* my... Ugh, who cares. I'll dispose of you after this, anyway. As I will with all of those who disrespect my authority. I'm not interested in the history of that foolish human waste, so it looks like we're done here."
"You should be proud. He was just as garbage as you, just as much of a coward. ...But he actually managed to kill his dad, so I guess you're still coming up short."

"Voreverl Leocot does not have a father in any real sense. John Leiblich may have provided the seed for this body, but it is not even my original form. I simply stole his daughter's life away, that's all there is to it. He has no more relation to me than the factory workers who made my villainous attire."

"Not really. You can never escape what made you, raised you. I don't care about your sci-fi origin story, Jane. I never knew a fuckin' infant. That's not the girl I knew or the girl I hated. It's your family that ruined my life, you included. That ruined the life of an entire lineage. Isn't that funny? It is, isn't it? Maybe you should do that obnoxious cringeworthy laugh about it."

She cocks her head to the side "It's... nice to know my presence has enough sheer potent evil energy to ruin your life, but... Uh, I mean... I can't find it funny if I don't know what you're talking about. Was there some scheme I forgot I played on you?"

"Of course you did. You took her from me. And then your father did. And none of that would ever have happened if it wasn't for everything else... if it wasn't for an absurd coincidence. The butterfly flapping its wings on the other side of the world. If your grandfather hadn't been a lunatic, a shitty one-dimensional fuckin' psychopath that set off events that would lead to a medical practitioner similarly losing his mind and abandoning his progeny to poverty." She picks up the box from earlier. "But I guess I should thank you. Now I know what I'm supposed to do. It shouldn't really be me here. But since it is, there's only really one ending."
She slides it in your direction with considerable effort. "Brought you a gift."

It topples over onto the ground still a reasonable distance from you, spilling its contents with a loud clattering. This thing is full of a somewhat obscene amount of close range combat weapons. There's daggers, a full on sword, a metal bat... almost anything you could think of. It's impressive this all could be acquired, and also how efficiently it was packed in there.

"I'm gonna kill you. Okay? Do your best to stop me."
Voreverl's eyes widen. She doesn't hesitate this time. No clever comebacks or stuttering surprise. She knows what she has to do.
Voreverl Leocot makes a break for the stairs.
Voreverl runs into the door, which is locked. This is confusing for multiple reasons.
"...Gweh... heh... good! Now you can't run away like a coward! Just... making sure we have a real cage match on our hands here!"

“Sure.” Her fists glint in the setting sunlight. “I still can’t bring myself to say her name. I don’t deserve it, Jane. See, I’m kind of a fucking monster. So seeing you play around like this… it’s a little irritating. Like appropriating someone’s culture.”

"...That so? 'Cause I'm thinking it over, Vi, and you know what? You've got a pretty bona fide genuine heroic origin story on your hands. Revenge against the evil lineage that rules the land, oppressing your family. Yes... yes! You're so much better than that pirate, or that... girl, the blondie... whatever her face." She approaches the pile of weapons and searches for a shortsword "But guess what, champ? The hero *always* loses. Darth Vader cuts off Luke's hand and throws him down a pit! Thanos kills half of all life! Scar kills Mufasa! You've made your own funeral with all this dramatic finale talk!"

“Good.” She doesn’t dignify most of that with a response.

There’s a shortsword.

Voreverl brandishes her weapon of choice, one of the only ones she's at all familiar with using. "Better hope you're not overestimating your readiness for a fight to the death. Voreverl Leocot's heist is about to begin! The greatest one she's pulled since I took... Ah, yes, it was her hair ribbon, wasn't it? Alice's, that is. I'll steal your life like I stole your childhood friend's most valuable possession! What a fitting end! You should be grateful I put so much thought into your execution."
She smiles. “Thanks, Jane.” Her expression darkens as she puts her fists up. “Maybe you’ll actually be able to amount to something.”
Voreverl grits her teeth, tightens her grip, and begins her attack. She rushes Violetta with the sword, and attempts to plunge it into her.

Violetta leaps out of the way. She haphazardly swipes at Voreverl, but it isn’t able to connect. “Just because I arranged this doesn’t mean I’m just gonna *give* it to you. Are you even trying?” She puts some distance between the two of you, which isn’t actually very smart since she needs an even closer range to be effective. “Hey, if you need motivation, killing me will mean you’ve committed two crimes total. That doubles your count. Big gain for evil, right? Pfahahaha!”

"You're the only one who needs motivation here! That's what makes heroes like you so weak! Evil rises out of nothing! You'll learn all about it once your world goes dark!" Voreverl rushes closer for another attempted impalement.

“I just want you to shut the fuck up. It’s a stronger motive than you. I know you never gave a shit about me. Really appreciate you making the time anyway.”

Voreverl is now.  closer.

"Never gave a shit about you? What did you expect? It's no fun to prank the school bully. You just would have... I mean, it's not like I'd be snuffing out any purity in the world, you know?" She stabs what she is aiming to be Violetta.

She knocks the blade away with her fist. It’s unconventional, and does leave that hand bleeding even as she tried to center it on the brass knuckles. “Hrr… I wasn’t a bully, you fuck. I was a realist, and I only REALLY antagonized you, and I only did it because you deserve it. If you’re too much of a pansy to handle people hating you, maybe you should stop trying to make that happen, hm? But it’s fine. I’m used to being secondary in priority. Every fucking time.” She accentuates ‘fucking’ with a literal gut punch. using her other hand. It doesn’t draw blood, but it almost certainly bruises.

"Gwgh... Hatred isn't my goal, just a side effect of fear. People fear what they don't understand, so I bet you're terrified of your place! Tell you what, let me make the pecking order clear here. You're not my first priority, true, but you're hardly my second. Even top ten would be a stretch! So, please, don't flatter yourself!" A third stab has hit Violetta's general direction.

This connects. It penetrates her shirt and continues onward to create a sizable wound in her abdomen. It’s shallow, but the kind of thing that will cause serious problems if not treated. It knocks the air out of her, but she refocuses her vision quickly.

She uppercuts you in the jaw. “Maybe this’ll shut you up?” It miraculously doesn’t actually prevent you from speaking. It is, however, excruciating. She kicks you away, and with you, the blade.

But she… ohhh, she wouldn’t *ever*… Comes with being immature, I guess! It’s a sort of personality that appeals to a child. *(cough)* You’ve done a great job staying the exact! Fucking! Same! Right down to your first instinct being to run away, too! Hahaha!” She sidesteps around Voreverl. “…Only pitied at first, I guess. Obviously things have changed.”

With her skull throbbing, it becomes hard for Voreverl to focus on the words for a comeback. "Yeah... well... you..." Her eyes center on the hole punctured in Violetta "...should see a doctor... I mean, I'd send one of the zoo animals to the vet for that... Get better for our, uh, final battle... I can't demonstrate my full power on a crippled foe!"
